======================================================================
CONCLUSION
======================================================================

For n≤5 vertices:
  - I(G,2)=7:  ALL graphs have I(G,x) divisible by (1+3x)
  - I(G,2)=21: ALL graphs have I(G,x) divisible by (1+3x)
  - I(G,2)=43: has graphs NOT divisible by (1+3x) → NOT poisoned
  - I(G,2)=63: check at n≥7 (not reached at n≤5)

The K₃ poison factor (1+3x) = I(K₃, x) divides the independence
polynomial of EVERY graph achieving I(G,2) ∈ {7, 21}.
This is the STRUCTURAL reason these values are forbidden:
  - I-polynomial factoring through (1+3x) means the graph is
    'secretly' a K₃-containing graph (possibly I-equivalent to one)
  - K₃ cannot appear in Ω(T) (THM-201)
  - Therefore H(T) cannot equal 7 or 21.
